Consciousness includes observations, thoughts, emotions, and intentions in biopsychology. It's awareness of oneself, environment, and mental moods. The "neural correlates" of consciousness are the brain activity and neurological processes linked with consciousness. This might include identifying the brain areas and neural circuits active during distinct conscious states and investigating how these neural processes create consciousness. Neuroimaging, neuropsychology, and electrophysiology may study consciousness experimentally. These approaches let researchers study neural activity and brain areas related to perception, attention, and memory. Functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) was used to research the neurological correlates of visual awareness. Using fMRI, this research may show participants pictures or patterns. Versus discover the brain areas and neural networks related with visual awareness, researchers might compare the brain activity of people who are aware of the visual stimuli to those who are not. Tsuchiya and Koch's 2006 research on visual awareness' brain correlates utilized a similar technique. When individuals reported being aware of the visuals, the primary visual cortex (V1) was more active in an fMRI. This research shows that V1 is involved in visual consciousness and that fMRI may be utilized to examine consciousness. 